==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pelagian
<hw>Pe*la"gi*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pelagius</ets>, Gr. <grk>pela`gios</grk>, fr. <grk>pe`lagos</grk>
the sea: cf. F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧lagien</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining
to the sea; marine; pelagic; <as>as, <ex>pelagian</ex>
shells</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pelagian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pelagian
<hw>Pe*la"gi*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>Pelagianus</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>p⟦eacute⟧lagien</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>A
follower of <etsep>Pelagius</etsep>, a British monk, born in the later
part of the 4th century, who denied the doctrines of hereditary sin, of
the connection between sin and death, and of conversion through
grace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pelagian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pelagian
<hw>Pe*la"gi*an</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧lagien</ets>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to Pelagius, or
to his doctrines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pelagianism</ent>⟦br⟧
